Solve this problem:

{
  "problem_text": "A drunkard walking in a narrow lane takes 5 steps forward and 3 steps backward, followed again by 5 steps forward and 3 steps backward, and so on. Each step is $1 \\text{ m}$ long and requires $1 \\text{ s}$. Plot the $x-t$ graph of his motion. Determine graphically and otherwise how long the drunkard takes to fall in a pit $13 \\text{ m}$ away from the start.",
  "options": []
}

{"steps": [{"step_type": "conceptual", "nudge_hint": "Can you group the drunkard's forward and backward steps into a single repeating cycle? What is the net distance covered and the total time taken in one full cycle?", "explanation": "In one cycle:
- Forward motion: $5$ steps $= 5$ $m$ in $5$ $s$.
- Backward motion: $3$ steps $= 3$ $m$ in $3$ $s$.
- Net displacement per cycle $= 5$ $m - 3$ $m = 2$ $m$.
- Total time per cycle $= 5$ $s + 3$ $s = 8$ $s$.", "step_number": 1, "latex_formula": "$$ 
\begin{aligned} 
\text{Net displacement per cycle} &= 5\text{ m} - 3\text{ m} = 2\text{ m} \\ 
\text{Total time per cycle} &= 5\text{ s} + 3\text{ s} = 8\text{ s} 
\end{aligned} 
$$"}, {"step_type": "calculation", "nudge_hint": "If the drunkard advances $2$ meters every $8$ seconds, where will he be after $4$ full cycles? Why should we be careful not to just divide $13$ meters by $2$ meters/cycle?", "explanation": "- After $1$ cycle: Position $= 2$ $m$, Time $= 8$ $s$.
- After $2$ cycles: Position $= 4$ $m$, Time $= 16$ $s$.
- After $3$ cycles: Position $= 6$ $m$, Time $= 24$ $s$.
- After $4$ cycles: Position $= 8$ $m$, Time $= 32$ $s$.", "step_number": 2, "latex_formula": "$$ 
\begin{aligned} 
\text{Position after } n \text{ cycles} &= n \times 2\text{ m} \\ 
\text{Time after } n \text{ cycles} &= n \times 8\text{ s} 
\end{aligned} 
$$"}, {"step_type": "calculation", "nudge_hint": "After $4$ cycles, he is at $8$ meters. How far is he from the $13$-meter pit, and how many forward steps will it take him to reach it in his next cycle?", "explanation": "After $4$ cycles, the drunkard is at $x = 8$ $m$ and the time elapsed is $t = 32$ $s$.
The remaining distance to the pit is $13$ $m - 8$ $m = 5$ $m$.
The next phase of motion is $5$ steps forward. This will cover exactly $5$ $m$.
Time taken for these $5$ steps $= 5$ $s$.", "step_number": 3, "latex_formula": "$$ 
\begin{aligned} 
\Delta x_{\text{remaining}} &= 13\text{ m} - 8\text{ m} = 5\text{ m} \\ 
\Delta t_{\text{final}} &= 5\text{ s} 
\end{aligned} 
$$"}, {"step_type": "calculation", "nudge_hint": "Since he falls into the pit during the forward phase of his $5$th cycle, what is the total time elapsed?", "explanation": "The drunkard reaches the pit at the end of the forward phase of the $5$th cycle.
Total time $=$ Time for $4$ cycles $+$ Time for the final $5$ forward steps
Total time $= 32$ $s + 5$ $s = 37$ $s$.", "step_number": 4, "latex_formula": "$$ t_{\text{total}} = 32\text{ s} + 5\text{ s} = 37\text{ s} $$"}, {"step_type": "visual", "nudge_hint": "How would this forward-and-backward motion look on a position-time graph? Can you visualize the 'peaks' of his forward steps intersecting the $13$-meter line?", "explanation": "The $x-t$ graph would show a series of "sawtooth" patterns that are generally rising. Each cycle consists of a line with slope $+1$ $m/s$ for $5$ $s$, followed by a line with slope $-1$ $m/s$ for $3$ $s$. The peaks of these cycles would be at ($5$ $s$, $5$ $m$), ($13$ $s$, $7$ $m$), ($21$ $s$, $9$ $m$), ($29$ $s$, $11$ $m$). The final forward step starts at ($32$ $s$, $8$ $m$) and goes with a slope of $+1$ $m/s$. The line for this segment is $x - 8 = 1(t - 32)$. To find the time when $x = 13$, we set $13 - 8 = t - 32$, which gives $5 = t - 32$, so $t = 37$ $s$.", "step_number": 5, "latex_formula": "$$ x - 8 = 1 \times (t - 32) \implies 13 - 8 = t - 32 \implies t = 37\text{ s} $$"}], "final_answer": "The drunkard takes $37$ $s$ to fall into the pit."}

